To enable dragging for nodes in Sigma.js, you can use the `dragNodes` plugin. Here's how you can do it:

1. Import the `dragNodes` plugin:
```html
<script src="sigma.min.js"></script>
<script src="plugins/sigma.plugins.dragNodes.min.js"></script>
```
2. Create the Sigma.js instance and initialize the `dragNodes` plugin:
```javascript
var s = new sigma({
  // ...your sigma configuration options...
});

s.addPlugin(sigma.plugins.dragNodes, {
  // ...dragNodes plugin options...
});

s.refresh();
```
3. Make sure your nodes have the `drag` attribute set to `true`. You can set this attribute when defining your nodes:
```javascript
var nodes = [
  { id: 'n0', label: 'Node 0', x: 0, y: 0, size: 1, drag: true },
  { id: 'n1', label: 'Node 1', x: 1, y: 1, size: 1, drag: true },
  // ...other nodes...
];
s.graph.addNodes(nodes);
```
That's it! Now you should be able to drag the nodes in the graph.

Note: The `dragNodes` plugin also provides additional options to control the drag behavior and appearance, such as `dragNodeView` and `dragNodeBorderSize`. You can customize these options according to your needs.

Apologies for the confusion. Sigma.js does not have an official dragNodes plugin. However, you can achieve drag and drop functionality by implementing it yourself or by using a third-party library like interact.js.

Here's an example using interact.js to enable dragging for nodes in Sigma.js:

1. First, include the Interact.js library in your HTML file:
```html
<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/interactjs@1.10.11"></script>
```

2. Create a basic Sigma.js graph with some nodes and edges:
```javascript
const s = new sigma({
  container: 'graph-container',
  settings: {
    defaultNodeColor: '#ec5148'
  }
});

s.graph.addNode({
  id: 'n0',
  label: 'Node 0',
  x: 0,
  y: 0,
  size: 1
});

s.graph.addNode({
  id: 'n1',
  label: 'Node 1',
  x: 1,
  y: 1,
  size: 1
});

s.graph.addEdge({
  id: 'e0',
  source: 'n0',
  target: 'n1'
});

s.refresh();
```

3. Use Interact.js to enable dragging for the Sigma.js nodes:
```javascript
interact('.sigma-node')
  .draggable({
    // Enable dragging only when left mouse button is pressed
    ignoreFrom: '[data-sigma-ignore-drag]',
    allowFrom: '.sigma-node-draggable',
    cursorChecker: (action, interactable, element) => {
      return 'grab';
    },
    listeners: {
      start (event) {
        // Add custom styling when dragging starts
        event.target.classList.add('sigma-node-dragging');
      },
      move (event) {
        // Update the position of the dragged node in Sigma.js graph
        const target = event.target;
        const node = s.graph.nodes(target.getAttribute('data-node-id'));
        const newPosition = s.camera.viewportToWorld({
          x: event.clientX,
          y: event.clientY
        });

        node.x = newPosition.x;
        node.y = newPosition.y;

        // Refresh Sigma.js to update the layout
        s.refresh();
      },
      end (event) {
        // Remove custom styling when dragging ends
        event.target.classList.remove('sigma-node-dragging');
      }
    }
  });
```

4. Lastly, apply some CSS to style the dragged node and the cursor when dragging:
```html
<style>
  .sigma-node,
  .sigma-node-draggable {
    cursor: grab;
  }

  .sigma-node-draggable:active {
    cursor: grabbing;
  }

  .sigma-node-dragging {
    opacity: 0.7;
    // Add any additional styling for the dragged node
  }
</style>
```

With this setup, you should be able to drag and drop the nodes in your Sigma.js graph.

Certainly! Here's a simplified example that demonstrates drag and drop functionality for nodes in Sigma.js using plain JavaScript:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="utf-8">
  <title>Sigma.js Drag and Drop Example</title>
  <script src="https://cdnjs.cloudflare.com/ajax/libs/sigma.js/2.0.0/sigma.min.js"></script>
  <style>
    #graph-container {
      width: 400px;
      height: 300px;
      border: 1px solid #ccc;
    }
    .node {
      background-color: #ec5148;
      border: 2px solid #fff;
      border-radius: 16px;
      color: #fff;
      display: flex;
      align-items: center;
      justify-content: center;
      width: 32px;
      height: 32px;
      font-size: 14px;
    }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <div id="graph-container"></div>

  <script>
    const s = new sigma({
      container: 'graph-container'
    });

    const nodes = [
      { id: 'n0', label: 'Node 0', x: 0, y: 0 },
      { id: 'n1', label: 'Node 1', x: 100, y: 100 }
    ];

    const edges = [
      { id: 'e0', source: 'n0', target: 'n1' }
    ];

    // Add nodes and edges to Sigma.js graph
    nodes.forEach(node => s.graph.addNode(node));
    edges.forEach(edge => s.graph.addEdge(edge));

    // Render graph
    s.refresh();

    // Enable drag and drop functionality for nodes
    const container = document.getElementById('graph-container');
    let draggingNodeId = null;

    container.addEventListener('mousedown', (event) => {
      const target = event.target;
      if (target.classList.contains('node')) {
        draggingNodeId = target.getAttribute('data-node-id');
      }
    });

    container.addEventListener('mousemove', (event) => {
      if (draggingNodeId) {
        const node = s.graph.nodes(draggingNodeId);
        const newPosition = s.camera.viewportToWorld({
          x: event.clientX,
          y: event.clientY
        });

        node.x = newPosition.x;
        node.y = newPosition.y;
        s.refresh();
      }
    });

    container.addEventListener('mouseup', () => {
      draggingNodeId = null;
    });
  </script>
</body>
</html>
```

In this simplified example, we directly use the mouse events for dragging nodes. When the mouse is pressed down on a node, we set the `draggingNodeId` variable to the corresponding node ID. As we move the mouse, if `draggingNodeId` is set, we update the position of the node in Sigma.js graph based on the mouse coordinates. Finally, we reset `draggingNodeId` when the mouse is released.

Note that this example uses a basic styling for the nodes. You can customize the node styling and add additional features as per your requirements.

